. (ii) perhaps a variant of   Huyton  , as the name of Huyton in Blackrod (Lancs) is also recorded as Highton; see   Lancs Place-Names  , p. 45."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen de Huyton was born in 1178, in Huyton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married John de Baguley in 1195, in Huyton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in July 1252, in Knutsford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1178–July 1252":"1178–juuli 1252","1172–Male":"1172–Surnud","1196–1263":"1196–1263","1178–1252":"1178–1252","July 1252":"juuli 1252","1178":"1178","1252":"1252","1263":"1263","1196":"1196","1195":"1195","1172":"1172","Baguley, Bucklow, Cheshire, England [Parents: John Baguley, Ellen Baguley]":"Baguley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Huyton, Lancashire, England":"Huyton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Knutsford, Cheshire, England":"Knutsford, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United K